        "id": "8a0f9353-6996-459a-81c3-708a0290e6a6",
        "score": 0.645005,
        "text": "The document page discusses two main services related to Distributed Energy Resources (DER) in the context of the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO):\n\n### 3.1. Energy Resource Interconnection Service (ERIS) for DER\n- ERIS can be obtained through NYISO's standard Small Generator Interconnection Procedures (SGIP) for individual DERs.\n- DERs must accept cost responsibility for any necessary upgrades to address reliability issues from interconnection.\n- The ERIS value is documented in the Interconnection Agreement.\n- DERs studied through non-NYISO procedures can still obtain an \"ERIS-equivalent\" value.\n- Further details are available in NYISO's Transmission Expansion and Interconnection Manual and other guides.\n\n### 3.2. Capacity Resource Interconnection Service (CRIS) for DER\n- CRIS can be obtained via Attachment S of the Open Access Transmission Tariff (OATT) if DERs accept cost responsibility for required upgrades.\n- DERs of 2MW or less can obtain CRIS without a deliverability study.\n- Non-NYISO interconnected DERs must be studied for deliverability unless smaller than 2MW.\n- Demand Side Resources in the Capacity market do not need CRIS; their Installed Capacity (ICAP) is based on maximum output during a DMNC test.\n- For DER aggregations with energy duration limits, the maximum CRIS request is based on the minimum of expected maximum injection capability, nameplate capacity, or the sum of requested and existing ERIS.\n\nThe document provides references to various manuals and guides for more detailed information.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Aggregation_Manual/page_24.jpg",
          "page_num": 24,
          "title": "Aggregation Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "45688d73-caf1-4ac9-a8fe-39a28aff999a",
        "score": 0.6288098,
        "text": "The document page outlines the procedures and requirements for SCR (Special Case Resource) Demand Response Payments by the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Key points include:\n\n1. **Local Generator Participation**: If an SCR is involved with a Local Generator, documentation of the generator's capacity is required.\n\n2. **Payment Conditions**: Payments are made to the Resource's Responsible Interface Party (RIP) for energy reductions during events or tests, provided the necessary data is submitted to the Demand Response Information System (DRIS) by a specified deadline.\n\n3. **Verification**: Payments depend on verified performance during the requested time period. If an SCR participates in the Day-Ahead Demand Response Program (DADRP) or the Day-Ahead Scheduling and Pricing (DSASP), payments are adjusted accordingly.\n\n4. **Calculation Methodology**: The Customer Base Load (CBL) calculation is detailed in the NYISO Emergency Demand Response Manual. The RIP must use a specific file format for data submission, as outlined in the NYISO DRIS User's Guide.\n\n5. **Energy Payment Computation**: Payments are based on the load reduction during the event, measured hourly. If the event lasts more than four hours, payments are made for the entire verified duration.\n\n6. **Short Events**: For events lasting four hours or less, SCRs that provide verified load reduction are paid as if activated for the full duration.\n\nThe document emphasizes adherence to specific procedures and timelines for data submission and performance verification to ensure proper payment.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_203.jpg",
          "page_num": 203,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ac6d61c9-86f0-4401-96ec-0453922296a1",
        "score": 0.61294544,
        "text": "The document outlines the interconnection process for Distributed Energy Resources (DER) facilities with the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Interconnection is allowed through the NYISO Small Generator Interconnection Procedure (SGIP) or other approved procedures. Interconnection studies must be completed and approved before DER enrollment in the Aggregation System. The process uses interconnection study data to validate DER characteristics. Aggregators must provide additional interconnection information to the Distribution Utility if requested. The focus is on facility-level requirements, not asset-level, and specific requirements apply to resources with energy duration limitations. DER facilities solely comprising Demand Side Resources are exempt from certain interconnection studies. A diagram illustrates the relationship between assets, DER facilities, and aggregation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Aggregation_Manual/page_23.jpg",
          "page_num": 23,
          "title": "Aggregation Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3647f38a-b403-4232-8d35-aef1e3f5c8ea",
        "score": 0.60165095,
        "text": "The document contains two main recommendations:\n\n1. **Eliminate Transaction Fees for CTS at PJM-NYISO Border**: The Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) process with PJM has not met expectations since its implementation in 2014, partly due to high transaction fees. Eliminating these fees, as done between ISO-NE and NYISO, could increase profitability and utilization of CTS transactions. High fees have led to lower usage and increased costs for renewable generators exporting surplus power, impacting REC costs for ratepayers. The recommendation is to remove these fees to enhance efficiency and reduce costs.\n\n2. **Dynamically Adjust Operating Reserve Requirements**: The NYISO should modify its market software to optimize reserve procurement by considering unused import capability as reserves. This adjustment could reduce costs by using local resources more efficiently. The recommendation includes evaluating the need for longer lead-time reserve products, suggesting a 30-minute reserve requirement in market models to better represent these needs. This aims to improve the efficiency of reserve management and reduce unnecessary costs.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_162.jpg",
          "page_num": 162,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0f4e4c04-660d-4344-a06e-7957b5a3fcff",
        "score": 0.59868795,
        "text": "The document discusses several key issues related to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) and its operations:\n\n1. **Export Fees and CTS Transactions**: NYISO's high export fees, amounting to $0.8 million in 2021, may reduce revenues from Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) transactions. Lower fees could increase profitability. The document suggests reducing transaction fees and uplift charges between PJM and NYISO to improve effectiveness.\n\n2. **Price Forecast Errors**: Errors at interfaces affect the effectiveness of CTS processes. Improving these processes is crucial for handling renewable output growth and balancing short-term fluctuations in intermittent generation.\n\n3. **PAR-Controlled Lines**: Phase angle regulators (PARs) are used to manage production costs. The operation of lines between Long Island and New York City increased costs and emissions in 2021. The report recommends exploring changes to the ConEd-LIPA wheeling agreement to enhance efficiency, especially with the growth of offshore wind and intermittent generation.\n\n4. **Out-of-Market Actions**: Guarantee payments to generators increased by 28% to $54 million in 2021, mainly due to higher natural gas prices. This was partially offset by reduced out-of-market commitments and dispatches.\n\nOverall, the document emphasizes the need for operational improvements and cost reductions to enhance efficiency and accommodate renewable energy growth.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2021/page_16.jpg",
          "page_num": 16,
          "title": "2021 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b536d318-203c-45b2-93c1-5f38c34bbe78",
        "score": 0.59784764,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures for qualifying and testing generation capacity in the Special Case Resources (SCR) program managed by the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Key points include:\n\n1. **Qualification of Local Generators**: \n   - Local Generators can be enrolled as capacity in the SCR program.\n   - The Responsible Interface Party (RIP) does not need to report generation used to serve the resource's load during NYCA or Locality peaks, as this is not eligible for SCR capacity.\n\n2. **Reporting Requirements**:\n   - The NYCA/Locality Peak Hour Load Generation Form must be used to report generation during peak hours.\n   - RIPs can enroll capacity up to the SCR\u2019s Net ACL or Provisional ACL.\n   - NYISO will notify the Transmission Owner to account for generation during peak hours.\n\n3. **Testing of SCRs**:\n   - SCRs must demonstrate their maximum enrolled megawatt value once per Capability Period.\n   - This can be shown through a mandatory event hour or a performance test hour.\n   - Additional tests may be required for SCRs with an Incremental ACL or a Change of Status.\n\n4. **Performance Tests**:\n   - Two tests are conducted per Capability Period: one between August 15 and September 7 (Summer) and another between February 15 and March 7 (Winter).\n   - A second test may occur in late September/October (Summer) or late March/April (Winter).\n\n5. **Energy Payments**:\n   - RIPs are eligible for payments if they provide all required data and comply with test-related requirements.\n\nThis section is part of the NYISO Installed Capacity Manual, detailing the operational and reporting standards for SCR participation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_191.jpg",
          "page_num": 191,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f555ba59-0aa3-494c-b50f-fbfc654d4f1f",
        "score": 0.5957267,
        "text": "The document discusses the process and results of the Class Year 2021 (CY21) study cycle related to deliverability and transmission planning for energy projects. It outlines the requirements for projects to pay for upgrades to receive Energy Resource Interconnection Service (ERIS) and Capacity Resource Interconnection Service (CRIS) rights. The study identifies necessary upgrades to ensure projects can deliver energy without violating transmission constraints.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The Class Year Study helps developers decide whether to pay for required upgrades, receive ERIS or CRIS rights, or withdraw.\n- Recent studies have taken about two years, with increasing numbers of participants and costs.\n- CY21 began in February 2021 and concluded in January 2023, with participants requesting 11 GW of ERIS and 10 GW of CRIS.\n- The CY21 SUF Study identified over $900 million in required upgrades, with $800 million for direct project connections and $100 million for systemwide reliability.\n- Sixteen projects requesting 4 GW of CRIS were not fully deliverable, with less than 400 MW partially deliverable.\n- NYISO identified $1.5 billion in System Deliverability Upgrades (SDUs) for these projects, with costs ranging from $468 to $2,557 per kW of UCAP.\n- The document includes a table summarizing the results and costs of the CY21 SDU Study.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_46.jpg",
          "page_num": 46,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "14a3f2e3-fafe-4901-874e-a94ec44c6355",
        "score": 0.5944435,
        "text": "This document page discusses deliverability and transmission planning related to the interconnection of energy projects, focusing on the categories of upgrades identified in the Cluster Study and Class Year process. The key points include:\n\n1. **Categories of Upgrades:**\n   - **Connecting Transmission Owner\u2019s Attachment Facilities (CTOAF):** Facilities required to connect a project to the transmission owner's network.\n   - **System Upgrade Facilities (SUF):** Network upgrades needed for projects to comply with NYISO\u2019s Minimum Interconnection Standard (MIS). Projects must pay allocated costs to receive the right to sell energy (ERIS). The MIS addresses reliability impacts but allows normal operating actions to avoid adverse effects.\n   - **System Deliverability Upgrades (SDU):** Upgrades required for resources to be deliverable under NYISO\u2019s Deliverability Interconnection Standard (DIS). Projects must pay for these upgrades to receive the right to sell capacity (CRIS). The DIS ensures that new and existing resources can deliver output without violating transmission constraints.\n\n2. **Process and Costs:**\n   - Developers must decide whether to pay for upgrades to receive ERIS or CRIS rights or withdraw from the study.\n   - The number of resources seeking interconnection and upgrade costs have increased recently.\n   - Class Year studies typically take about two years, while the Cluster Study aims for a 590-day timeline.\n   - New resources not part of an ongoing study must wait for a new study to begin.\n   - If SDUs are needed, a preliminary cost estimate is issued, and affected projects may enter an Additional SDU Study for final cost allocations.\n\n3. **Inefficient Upgrade Project Selection \u2013 Class Year 2023:**\n   - The most recent Class Year study (2023) started in January 2023 and finished in early 2025.\n   - Participants requested about 15 GW of ERIS and 14 GW of CRIS.\n   - The study identified $2.8 billion in CTOAF and SUF costs, with individual cost allocations ranging from $0 to $581 per kW of nameplate capacity, averaging $207 per kW.\n   - Proposed projects were generally fully deliverable except on Long Island, where an Additional SDU Study was necessary.\n\nThe page also includes references to additional details on the interconnection process and related study reports available on NYISO\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_50.jpg",
          "page_num": 50,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "43f20e2d-6be7-4d24-9080-34e7efa1062b",
        "score": 0.59289956,
        "text": "The document discusses pricing and settlement methods for capacity resources in Zone J, focusing on resource adequacy and transmission security. It outlines a scenario where the incremental price for resource adequacy is $5.60 per kW-month, and for transmission security, it's $7.50 per kW-month. Most Zone J resources receive the full clearing price of $19 per kW-month, while others receive $11.50 based on resource adequacy.\n\nThree hypothetical resources are illustrated:\n\n1. SCRs receive $11.50 per kW-month.\n2. A 1000 MW generator is paid for 720 MW at $19 per kW-month and 230 MW at $11.50.\n3. An 800 MW offshore wind unit is paid for 200 MW at $11.50 and 80 MW at $7.50.\n\nThe document recommends a two-part pricing method to separate payments for resource adequacy and transmission security, aiming to improve investment incentives and reduce overpayments.\n\nAdditionally, it critiques the NYISO's deliverability test methodology, noting its misalignment with resource adequacy analyses and its potential impact on estimating resources' deliverability as renewables and storage grow.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_371.jpg",
          "page_num": 371,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "03e95aab-401b-4280-a2fc-f239dc7ba838",
        "score": 0.59025127,
        "text": "The document page presents two scenarios related to transmission congestion: the Basecase Scenario and the PAR Relief Scenario.\n\n### Basecase Scenario:\n- **Gen/Load Payments:**\n  - **Upstate:** LBMP $25, Load 10,000, Generation 13,000, Revenue $250,000, Generator Payments $325,000.\n  - **NYC:** LBMP $30, Load 4,000, Generation 1,900, Revenue $120,000, Generator Payments $57,000.\n  - **Valley Stream:** LBMP $50, Load 350, Generation 150, Revenue $17,500, Generator Payments $7,500.\n  - **Rest of Long Is.:** LBMP $35, Load 2,500, Generation 1,800, Revenue $87,500, Generator Payments $63,000.\n  - **Total:** Load 16,850, Generation 16,850, Revenue $475,000, Generator Payments $452,500.\n  - **Net (Gen minus Load):** $0, Congestion Revenue $22,500.\n\n- **Transmission Revenue:**\n  - **Interfaces:** Dunwoodie, Y50, 262 Line, 901 Line Contract.\n  - **Shadow Prices and Flows:** Dunwoodie $5 (2,000), Y50 $10 (1,000), 262 Line $15 (300), 901 Line Contract -$20 (100).\n  - **Congestion Revenue:** Total $22,500.\n\n### PAR Relief Scenario (901 Line Flow Reduced from 100 MW to 10 MW):\n- **Gen/Load Payments:**\n  - **Upstate:** Same as Basecase.\n  - **NYC:** LBMP $30, Load 4,000, Generation 1,990, Revenue $120,000, Generator Payments $59,700.\n  - **Valley Stream:** LBMP $50, Load 350, Generation 60, Revenue $17,500, Generator Payments $3,000.\n  - **Rest of Long Is.:** Same as Basecase.\n  - **Total:** Load 16,850, Generation 16,850, Revenue $475,000, Generator Payments $450,700.\n  - **Net (Gen minus Load):** $0, Congestion Revenue $24,300.\n\n- **Transmission Revenue:**\n  - **Interfaces:** Dunwoodie, Y50, 262 Line, 901 Line Contract, 901 Line Adjust.\n  - **Shadow Prices and Flows:** Dunwoodie $5 (2,000), Y50 $10 (1,000), 262 Line $15 (300), 901 Line Contract -$20 (100), 901 Line Adjust -$20 (-90).\n  - **Congestion Revenue:** Total $24,300.\n\nBoth scenarios analyze the load, generation, and financial aspects of different nodes, focusing on congestion revenue and transmission interface flows.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_235.jpg",
          "page_num": 235,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

